  "prompt": "What is achilles tendonitis?",
  "response": "Achilles tendonitis is an inflammation or irritation of the Achilles tendon, which is the large tendon that connects the calf muscles to the back of the heel bone. This condition is often caused by overuse, particularly in activities that involve running or jumping, and can result in pain and stiffness in the affected area. \n\nCommon symptoms of Achilles tendonitis include:\n\n- Pain and swelling in the back of the heel, especially in the morning or after physical activity\n- Limited range of motion in the ankle\n- A warm or hot sensation in the affected area\n- Thickening of the tendon\n\nRisk factors for developing Achilles tendonitis include sudden increases in physical activity, improper footwear, tight calf muscles, and having flat feet or high arches. Treatment typically involves rest, ice, compression, and elevation (RICE), along with anti-inflammatory medication and physical therapy. In severe cases, surgery may be necessary to repair the damaged tendon.",
